<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[192,1440,1761,1914]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,335,1761,1785]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Wingspan 12.0– 
<quantity box="[537,644,1761,1785]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.95" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" unit="mm" value="19.5">19.5 mm</quantity>
. Adults are recognized by the presence of scattered spatulate dark and light scales mixed in with fringe scales along the anal margin of the hind wing third lobe as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Matthews and Landry." authorityName="Matthews and Landry." box="[192,659,1826,1850]" class="Insecta" family="Pterophoridae" genus="Exelastis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dowi">
<emphasis box="[192,369,1826,1850]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Exelastis dowi</emphasis>
Matthews and Landry.
</taxonomicName>
The forewing ground color is grayish-brown as opposed to light buff or ochraceous-buff. Worn specimens can be distinguished by genitalia characters as illustrated in 
<bibRefCitation author="Matthews, D. L. &amp; B. Landry" box="[192,556,1890,1914]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" pagination="62 - 70" refId="ref7494" refString="Matthews, D. L., and B. Landry. 2008. Description of a new species of Exelastis (Lepidoptera: Pterophoridae) from the neotropics, with keys to adults of the four species occurring in Florida. Tropical Lepidoptera Research 18 (2): 62 - 70." type="journal article" year="2008">Matthews and Landry (2008)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[193,1442,193,282]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[193,367,193,217]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Life History.</emphasis>
Larvae feed on leaves and shoots of 
<taxonomicName box="[812,1059,194,218]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Rhynchosia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="minima">
<emphasis box="[812,1059,194,218]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Rhynchosia minima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) DC [
<taxonomicName box="[1169,1292,194,218]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
]. The larvae are green with pale cream colored dorsal longitudinal bands. Both primary and secondary setae are noticeably bifurcate tipped, with abundant secondary setae both scattered and grouped on tubercles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
